title: Social & Emotional Development: Preschool domain
subject: Head Start Early Learning Outcomes Framework (2015-)

document.title: Head Start Early Learning Outcomes Framework Ages Birth to Five

28C6F2422FD34AD5B259B6378064CE86.description:
Identifies similarities and differences about
self across familiar environments and
settings.

259C5ED9ADDC4AB3A4654781BE603CEA.description:
Relates personal stories about being a part
of different groups.

5A7450063FAC42409C1E978733A3D656.description:
Identifies self as being a part of different
groups, such as family, community, culture,
faith, or preschool.

043F2E5C30D94491BD37DC7B2D415F2C.description:
48 to 60 Months: Has a sense of belonging to family and
community and communicates details
about these connections, such as
sharing a story about a family gathering,
both spontaneously and when prompted
by an adult or other child.

2F0A4B378AEA4628984677172891C33E.description:
36 to 48 Months: Communicates feeling a sense of
belonging to family and an emerging
sense of connections to other
communities through words or other
forms of expression, such as drawing
a picture of their family or sharing a
special object related to their cultural
heritage.

E86980FB38734060980C8DAC3AC88BE8.description: Child has sense of belonging to family, community, and other groups.

6358A70DBA2B4651ABF713AFE3BBAC01.description:
Uses positive words to describe self,
such as kind or hard-worker.

EFAE7E5BB79B43D88E2C8D14934DC903.description:
Expresses own ideas or beliefs in group
contexts or in interactions with others.

DB0E5CAA26494D638E66BA9AC950FEF7.description:
Shows satisfaction or seeks
acknowledgment when completing a
task or solving a problem.

A6037B2D994744D08AD7FFC36724420B.description:
48 to 60 Months: Enjoys accomplishing a greater
number of tasks and sharing these
accomplishments with other children
and adults. Makes increasing number
of contributions to group discussion
and may share ideas with or without
adult prompting.

8CE5FF90D3064A95BD28AECB5A98CF21.description:
36 to 48 Months: Expresses enjoyment in accomplishing
daily routines and new skills and
may draw adult attention to these
accomplishments. May share own
ideas or express positive feelings
about self, particularly when prompted
by an adult.

215523DB654F40DCBF88375A515C4D44.description: Child expresses confidence in own skills and positive feelings about self.

B292399071BB47978FF0CFB437D8AB8A.description:
Demonstrates knowledge of uniqueness
of self, such as talents, interests,
preferences, or culture.

1A35A10F96B844D9A85C1AE0AC0050F6.description:
Describes self using several different
characteristics.

426D6A1AD3B24A30910795CF35EDC5A0.description:
48 to 60 Months: Describes a larger range of individual
characteristics and interests and
communicates how these are similar or
different from those of other people.

CFD676E2CDB544E98F1FDD9824452353.description:
36 to 48 Months: Describes own physical characteristics
and behaviors and indicates likes and
dislikes when asked.

9A6B8C63272C4A84BD1AC94CE97C5706.description: Child recognizes self as a unique individual having own abilities, characteristics, emotions, and interests.

60E821F786B44F499BBAFB9E6D086CEC.description:
Uses a range of coping strategies to
manage emotions with the support of an
adult, such as using words or taking a
deep breath.

754055121E264A85930A9530B67636C4.description:
Looks for adult assistance when feelings
are most intense.

564B21B30B074CA4870912FE2725103D.description:
Expresses feelings in ways that are
appropriate to the situation.

66E87B993ADD4753A9B1B0B3403B7D7C.description:
48 to 60 Months: Has an expanding range of strategies
for managing emotions, both less
intense emotions and those that cause
greater distress. Sometimes looks to
adults for support in managing the
most intense emotions, but shows
increasing skill in managing emotions
independently.

F6544A128CC64DD68E9773952E974F75.description:
36 to 48 Months: Manages less intense emotions, such
as mild frustration, independently. May
require adult support to manage more
intense emotions.

2E5A4FD8EFDD4EC4A8F48538ED2CEC98.description: Child manages emotions with increasing independence.*

ED91A181715B4C60BD4389126F20DDAD.description:
Offers support to adults or other children
who are distressed.

510C3B1E67DD4BA7B6818BD5EE62F637.description:
Makes empathetic statements to adults
or other children.

2AB6F065301E4297A04CBE8009D5986C.description:
48 to 60 Months: Consistently pays attention when
others are distressed and often
responds with care, either by seeking
out adult support or providing
reassurance or support themselves.

E129792312114A26B53FAA73CC19C15B.description:
36 to 48 Months: Often pays attention when others are
distressed, but attention and response
to this distress may be brief. May seek
out adult support to help another child
who is distressed.

4CA9B992FE4F41D9B27AE80A7C9FAD5F.description: Child expresses care and concern toward others.

462A9C5C9D37453EA2B25CE37F3D827F.description:
Uses words to describe the feelings of
adults or other children.

C67B165DA636476E915796FD2781E43B.description: Uses words to describe own feelings.

E41180F5D31E448E998EE9B38918D223.description:
Recognizes and labels basic emotions
in books or photographs.

DC667FEF70ED40C982C0AE5B13CB710F.description:
48 to 60 Months: Expresses a broad range of emotions
and begins to notice more subtle or
complex emotions in self and others,
such as embarrassed or worried. Uses
words to describe own feelings when
prompted, and may at times use these
words without prompting, such as
saying “Don’t be mad” when engaged
in play with other children.

91D4EB45B9EC49B7ACCCA71EF75FF517.description:
36 to 48 Months: Expresses a broad range of emotions
across contexts, such as during play
and in interactions with adults. Notices
when strong emotions are exhibited
by others and begins to use words to
describe some of these emotions, such
as happy, sad, or mad.

7932C2FA91414AA4ABE37DC44E222BB6.description: Child expresses a broad range of emotions and recognizes these emotions in self and others.

8B14224A1BF244D68C7D2631B359750A.description:
Seeks adult help when needed to
resolve conflicts.

9308F37A1CDD4ADEA2B5ADEBAF733793.description:
Expresses feelings, needs, and opinions
in conflict situations.

E196E9E962F24CAE98F9C715C5F1BC6A.description:
Uses basic strategies for dealing with
common conflicts, such as sharing,
taking turns, and compromising.

887A12D9915347E9960629CB618F7A2D.description:
Recognizes and describes basic social
problems in books or pictures, such as
both children wanting the same toy, and
during interactions with other children,
such as “Why do you think your friend
might be sad?”

71A97C8BC8A44F73B5CEED0AE76B7F78.description:
48 to 60 Months: Often recognizes and describes
social problems, suggests solutions
to conflicts, and compromises when
working or playing in a group. Although
simple conflicts may be resolved
without adult assistance, may seek
out or need adult support in more
challenging moments.

86C8300EC69B420E8C99CBBB19BFC13E.description:
36 to 48 Months: Begins to recognize and describe
social problems. Suggests solutions
to conflicts with adult guidance and
support.

86D6F43496DC4F80AF60F3685FCDF359.description: Child uses basic problem-solving skills to resolve conflicts with other children.

4C226202AAAE4FD4AD9AAE036A4670D2.description:
Engages in reflection and conversation
about past play experiences.

E0F750BD8DBE484DBB12B62EE052E23E.description:
Shows enjoyment of play with other
children, such as through verbal
exchanges, smiles, and laughter.

7A907D42BB5E49408A2AC116B2876C0D.description:
Demonstrates willingness to include
others’ ideas during interactions and
play.

3A68AC3098B243169F6E5A666ADC66B3.description:
Engages in joint play, such as using
coordinated goals, planning, roles, and
games with rules, with at least one other
child at a time.

D622835BC01A4860B2D3063E48FB2D0B.description:
48 to 60 Months: Cooperatively plays with other children
in an increasingly coordinated way.
Works with other children to make
plans for what and how they will play
together. When given the opportunity,
these coordinated play periods get
longer.

238F3509ECFC47A7B6BA5ECFDF2B6C35.description:
36 to 48 Months: Often plays cooperatively with other
children. For at least short periods
during this play, works with other
children to plan and enact this play
in a coordinated way.

ACB497D6108740A3BAE7C76ADFADF153.description: Child engages in cooperative play with other children.

E75DDBF1F8BB4DF5AE43E9FF6FC06488.description:
Develops friendships with one or two
preferred other children.

2525D08D93064848AA8656EC3A5392AA.description:
Takes turns in conversations and
interactions with other children.

5DB483CCD8724E99909B561717EC1FF2.description:
Uses a variety of skills for entering
social situations with other children,
such as suggesting something to do
together, joining an existing activity,
or sharing a toy.

9A6039A02AF44056BDEEB9486406B8C3.description:
Engages in and maintains positive
interactions with other children.

687C21B4C3F54F5FA399571AFB41B347.description:
48 to 60 Months: Sustains interactions with other
children more often and for increasing
periods of time. Demonstrates prosocial
behaviors with other children with and
without prompting from adults. Likely
to show at least some preference for
playing with particular children.

379A6AD68EE6469187EEB9038A77FFA7.description:
36 to 48 Months: Sometimes engages in and maintains
interactions with other children without
support from an adult, or demonstrates
skills in doing this when prompted by
an adult. May spontaneously engage in
prosocial behaviors with other children,
such as sharing and taking turns with
materials and in conversations, or may
engage in these with prompting from
adults.

4906857CE1244293A630669BBF9715C6.description: Child engages in and maintains positive interactions and relationships with other children.

303D05A7F3B14BFAB1895BEC873BC9C5.description:
Asks or waits for adult permission before
doing something when they are unsure.

7F827653D52048C5B2A7107FC7A24B6F.description:
Follows adult guidelines and
expectations for appropriate behavior.

2233606809D4487EAE683C0879220D33.description: Attends to an adult when asked.

A2B66F3103A54FD0978A8C6733649598.description:
Engages in prosocial behaviors with
adults, such as using respectful
language or greetings.

42A4711654D8409DA087D8A26A62C76D.description:
48 to 60 Months: Often engages in prosocial
behavior with adults and usually
responds appropriately to adult
requests and directions without
significant assistance or prompting.
Uncooperative behavior with familiar
adults is rare and the child is able to
resolve minor conflicts with adults
with support, such as being given
reminders to use a quiet voice or
follow directions.

1A4DD8344205473CB97BB4429B1B25EB.description:
36 to 48 Months: Sometimes engages in prosocial
behavior with adults, such as greeting
the teacher or saying goodbye,
and responds to adult requests
and directions that may include
assistance or prompting. Sometimes
demonstrates uncooperative behavior
with familiar adults, such as saying
“No” to requests, but these moments
are typically resolved with support
from adults.

BC2B86FBFD5446968A1EDC2D45DA78E2.description: Child engages in prosocial and cooperative behavior with adults.

8DB963905492489BB4925E30BE187281.description: Seeks help from adults when needed.

1693FCEF7698419E8747BFF16018B0F0.description:
Shows affection and preference for
adults who interact with them on a
regular basis.

ECB1E9606D814DD78D300963AF463ECE.description:
Engages in some positive interactions
with less familiar adults, such as parent
volunteers.

BEA88625939D4447B01DA6F22913D9E7.description:
48 to 60 Months: Clearly shows enjoyment in
interactions with trusted adults
while also demonstrating skill in
separating from these adults with
minimal distress when in a familiar
setting. Initiates interactions with
adults and participates in longer
and more reciprocal interactions
with both trusted and new adults.

5BFD93C8322B42ADA20115984819A473.description:
36 to 48 Months: Engages in positive interactions with
adults, such as by demonstrating
affection or talking about ideas. Is able
to separate from trusted adults when
in familiar settings. Uses adults as a
resource to solve problems.

28DA0E505230459EB117FE635CBFF67B.description: Child engages in and maintains positive relationships and interactions with adults.
